<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=176156447&t=artid%3d8bc3f7a4-68e4-483c-a7bf-3775cc61bec0%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=176156447&t=artid%3d8bc3f7a4-68e4-483c-a7bf-3775cc61bec0%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>But those who attended, after waiting for a long time to see him, were told the minister was not coming to the event.Deputy police minister Bongani Mkongi came in his place instead.Addressing a crowd at Wanderers Taxi Rank, Mkongi said the anti-crime operation campaign was launched in October. “We called it a safer festive season campaign because when it’s the festive season everyone wants to take chances.”He said they wanted people to be safe during the holidays.“But we can’t make sure of that on our own as the police,” said Mkongi. “We need you as our people to be vigilant and report crime.” He said people should stop flashing their wallets.“Hide your wallet in order to be safe from criminals,” he said.He advised people not to go around asking anyone for directions, let alone carrying their bags.“Like here at Park Station, there are boys who wear nice clothes that look like they were bought in Italy,” he said. “Those clothes are fake and clean. “They wake up in the morning to stand here and pretend to be helpers. Don’t accept their help.”Mkongi advised the attentive crowd to rather ask the police if they needed help.He told them that police had arrested many thugs since the operation started.
